3. Homo Deo mistus t ‘ man united to God’3 miscere recurs in this sense ch. 393 adv. Maro. ii. 27, ‘ miscente in semetipso Hominem et Deum.’ This was the usual expression of the early Latin Fathers for the Union of the Two Natures in Christ, corresponding to κρᾶσις (and its compounds) of the Greek Fathers. As used by them this phrase- ology was perfectly orthodox ; e. 9. S. Cyprian de. idol. van. 11 ; Orig. contr. Cels. iii. 41; Lactant. iv. 133 S. Athan. Orat. e. Ar. iv· 333 contr. Apol. ii. 16 (Lib. Fath. Later Treat. p. 138); and even later by S. August. Ep. 137. 11 ; S. Greg. Naz. Ep. 101. 103 S. Greg. Nyss. Cat. 273 S. Leo serm. 23. 1 (Bright’s transl. note 9); comp. S. Cyr- Alex. adm. Nest. i. 3. But the terms were subsequently abused by heresy and invested with a technical heretical meaning3 and it then became necessary to restrict the Catholic phraseology to exactly defined expressions. Thus ’ἐνωσις καθ’ ὑπόστασιν, unitio, were the orthodox terms by which the Personal Union was expressed, and the heretical expressions were disclaimed: κρᾶσις as Apollinarian; συναφεῖα, associ- atio, as Nestorian3 σύγχυσις, commixtio, as Eutychian. See Liddon Bampt. Leet. vii. pp. 426 ff.
